From: Miro Mraz <mraz.miro@seznam.cz>
Subject: [PATCH v3 0/2] Pixel 4a (sunfish): enable FTM5 touchscreen on mainline

Sits on top of David Heidelberg's v4 stmfts5 series
(20260409-stmfts5-v4-0-64fe62027db5@ixit.cz on linux-input). Both fixes
were found while bringing up the touchscreen on a Google Pixel 4a
(sunfish, FTM5CU56AA1BE, chip ID 0x4836) running postmarketOS with the
sm7150-mainline 7.1-rc3 kernel.

PATCH 1 (driver):
  Replaces the single I2C read after reset with a poll loop in
  stmfts5_configure. The chip's firmware boot includes internal CRC
  verification of flash sections and can take a few hundred ms before
  its I2C state machine ACKs; the single read races the firmware and
  loses, returning -ENXIO silently. Polling at 25 ms intervals for up
  to ~500 ms exits the moment CONTROLLER_READY arrives (average-case
  zero added delay) and -ETIMEDOUT cleanly in the bad case.

  Empirical aside in the commit body: on this chip the
  STMFTS_READ_ONE_EVENT register (0x85) never returns event data on a
  first post-reset read; only STMFTS_READ_ALL_EVENT (0x86) does. v4
  already uses 0x86 here, so this preserves that choice — flagging it
  in case anyone else tries to "simplify" to 0x85 later.

PATCH 2 (DT):
  Adds the sunfish DTS node and pinctrl. Two non-obvious bits:
  - VDD and AVDD are separate physical supplies sharing rails with the
    OLED panel (touch and display are one bonded assembly). VDD comes
    from vreg_l13a_1p8 (display vddio), AVDD from vreg_l7c_3p0 (display
    vdda-3p3). PM6150 GPIO 4 enables an external load switch upstream
    of these rails and is asserted via pinctrl rather than as a
    regulator-fixed, since the shared OLED supplies are already always
    on when the touchscreen probes.
  - mode-switch-gpios uses GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW. Empirically, driving the
    line HIGH puts the chip into SLPI-routed mode where the AP-side
    I2C address goes silent. LOW keeps it on the AP path.

End-to-end on Pixel 4a: with v4 + this series + Session A's PM6150
charger/qgauge DT changes, the device boots and the user can navigate
the postmarketOS UI by touch while charging works concurrently. The
combined kernel branch lives at:
  https://github.com/miromraz/linux/tree/sunfish-mainline

Change log:
  v3: address review of v1 — vreg_touch_en split into proper vdd/avdd
      supplies (David's feedback that "vreg_touch_en is not both digital
      vdd and analog avdd"); 500 ms blocking sleep replaced with the
      poll loop in PATCH 1 (David's feedback that the downstream driver
      reads chip state during the wait rather than blocking).
  v2: poll loop only; DTS unchanged.
  v1: initial post.

Signed-off-by: Miro Mraz <mraz.miro@seznam.cz>

